
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `iptables-xml` baraye tabdil kardan ghavanin `iptables` be formate XML estefade mishavad.  In formate XML mitavanad baraye backup gereftan, moratab kardan va taghire ghavanin `iptables` be asani estefade shavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `--file <filename>` --> 💾 Zakhire kardan khorooji XML dar yek file khass.
    🔹 `--stdout`       --> 📤 Chap kardan khorooji XML dar terminal (standard output).
    🔹 `--version`      --> ℹ️ Namayesh version barname.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ iptables-xml --stdout

    🔹 Tabdil ghavanin `iptables` be XML va chap an dar terminal.

    $ iptables-xml --file firewall.xml

    🔹 Zakhire kardan ghavanin `iptables` dar file-e `firewall.xml`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ iptables-xml --file backup.xml

    🔹 In dastoor ghavanin `iptables` ra be formate XML tabdil mikonad va dar file-e `backup.xml` zakhire mikonad.  In kar baraye backup gereftan az ghavanin firewall kheili mofid ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `iptables-xml` command is used to convert `iptables` rules to XML format. This XML format can be used to easily back up, manage, and modify `iptables` rules.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `--file <filename>` --> 💾 Save the XML output to a specific file.
    🔹 `--stdout`       --> 📤 Print the XML output to the terminal (standard output).
    🔹 `--version`      --> ℹ️ Display the program version.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ iptables-xml --stdout

    🔹 Convert `iptables` rules to XML and print it on the terminal.

    $ iptables-xml --file firewall.xml

    🔹 Save `iptables` rules to a file named `firewall.xml`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ iptables-xml --file backup.xml

    🔹 This command converts `iptables` rules to XML format and saves them in the file `backup.xml`. This is very useful for backing up firewall rules.

